If you haven’t heard this radio transmission, please take the time to listen. ⛔️Be cautioned it is hard to listen to.⛔️

The calm voice in the chaos  in Chicago during the incident that occurred on 8/7/2021. Thank you Dispatcher Keith Thornton - The way he took control of this incident and talked to his officers, kept his air completely shut down and clear, set a perimeter within seconds quite possibly is what resulted in the apprehension of the suspects. 

Dispatcher Keith Thornton was fast thinking and took initiative without any direction in the very beginning stages and ran the emergency like an actual incident commander - far beyond the criteria of any dispatcher. 

The world heard you loud and clear and we stand with you. 💙🖤💙🖤💙🖤💙

Vice President Kamala Harris doubled down and confirms to CNN that she was the “last person in the room” with President Biden when he made the decision to pull all US troops out of Afghanistan. Harris confirms she had key role in Biden's Afghanistan withdrawal decision

"All relevant points of view were heard and all arguments were put on the table," said one senior administration official who spoke to CNN on condition of anonymity.

President Joe Biden ordered the withdrawal of US forces from Afghanistan over the advice of some of his senior-most advisers in the Pentagon and State Department, leaders who are now charged with carrying out the particulars of the complicated drawdown.

Multiple current and former officials tell CNN that those advisers -- including Chairman of the Joint Chiefs Gen. Mark Milley, leader of US Central Command Gen. Frank McKenzie and some State Department officials -- expressed concerns about what a full withdrawal might mean for the US counter-terror mission. They also expressed concern about the security of US diplomats based there.

Warnings about the potential for the Taliban to regain power and for violence to increase pervaded the numerous meetings over the past few months, according to officials, though Biden continually chafed at suggestions US troops should remain in Afghanistan for much longer, according to people familiar with the matter, reminding his advisers that -- like his two predecessors -- he promised voters he would end the country's longest war, even if that meant going against the recommendations of his top generals.

Source: CNN ✅

node.text:
Even CNN can’t ignore this catastrophic debacle. CNN reported in April that Joe Biden went “his own way” on the Afghanistan withdrawal [So he needs to stop blaming Trump for his failures] 

"All relevant points of view were heard and all arguments were put on the table," said one senior administration official who spoke to CNN on condition of anonymity.

President Joe Biden ordered the withdrawal of US forces from Afghanistan over the advice of some of his senior-most advisers in the Pentagon and State Department, leaders who are now charged with carrying out the particulars of the complicated drawdown.

Multiple current and former officials tell CNN that those advisers -- including Chairman of the Joint Chiefs Gen. Mark Milley, leader of US Central Command Gen. Frank McKenzie and some State Department officials -- expressed concerns about what a full withdrawal might mean for the US counter-terror mission. They also expressed concern about the security of US diplomats based there.

Warnings about the potential for the Taliban to regain power and for violence to increase pervaded the numerous meetings over the past few months, according to officials, though Biden continually chafed at suggestions US troops should remain in Afghanistan for much longer, according to people familiar with the matter, reminding his advisers that -- like his two predecessors -- he promised voters he would end the country's longest war, even if that meant going against the recommendations of his top generals.

Source: CNN ✅
